lass=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 140<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(1/9/02 1:36:31 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1062.topic&index=10>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Guilds</span><hr size=1> Hail<br><br>My opinion has always been that the good name of a guild tag is more valuable than anything else imaginable in Norrath.  It's worth more than any possession, any accomplishment, any amount of &quot;experience&quot;.  As first officer of the Traders Union (which is the highest position I've ever held in a guild before) I found this even more true.  As a member of Starspun, I am proud to be in a guild which is respected and successful.  If I ever damaged that reputation, I'd feel guilt beyond measure.<br><br>I try not to judge an entire guild based on the actions of one member, but I do have some kind of sliding scale in my mind that tracks my experiences with guilds.  It's like guild faction.  And I always base my actions on the assumption that everyone I meet /is/ judging my whole guild based on my behavior.  Even if that isn't true, it might be, and it helps keep me on my toes.<br><br>That all being said, the idea that it's hard to form guilds on FV now isn't so surprising.  There are about 115 or so guilds on our server, or have been.  Some of those are no doubt dead.  But even if half of them are alive 60 or so guilds is probably more than enough for our relatively small population.  Yes, many people are still not in guilds, but perhaps many of them do not wish to be.  I certainly support anyone who is in the process of forming a guild (it is never easy) but I'm not surprised to hear it's getting harder.<br><br>And regarding the difficulty of getting to know or joining established guilds, Starspun's website is at www.geocities.com/starspunguild .  Anyone who wants to get to know us is encouraged to contact anyone with our guild tag and set about making time to group with us.  If you make the effort to seek us out, we'll be happy to make the effort to get to know you.  The same goes for almost any guild I can think of.  Some guilds will throw their tag on almost anyone who walks up to them and asks.  But not the good ones.  If it takes a week or two of making time to get to know a guild, so much the better.  Finding a few hoops to jump through means the guild is a good one.<br><br>Valquiss Silverpalm<br>Proud member of Starspun <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ukimayasilverbark.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Kimaya Silverbark</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 20<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(1/9/02 3:16:34 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1062.topic&index=11>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Guilds</span><hr size=1> A few words from someone who is still currently guildless:<br><br>The behaviour of your members is everything.<br><br>A lot of us have been burned in guilds before, both by joining a guild that turned out to be less well-behaved than we thought at first, and by a perfectly good guild being overrun by the poorly-behaved.  There are also some of us who have been burned in groups with (or by actions in the same zone as...) folks wearing guildtags.  I know the best thing to do would be to take it up with the guildleaders, just like the best thing to do when you receive poor service in RL is to take it up with the company.<br><br>But what do most us do?  Nothing -- we just decide to avoid those folks in the future.  Unfortunately, that sometimes includes entire guilds.  I know we shouldn't make generalizations like that, but we still do.<br><br>So now that I'm wondering if the right guild for me is already out there, I'm making a personal assessment of all the folks I've interacted with, as well as the tags above their heads.  Will I avoid those tags that have been over all the heads I didn't like?  Perhaps I shouldn't, but I probably will.  I just hope I don't pass up &quot;the right guild for me&quot; because of it.<br> <p>---<BR>Kimaya Silverbark<BR><BR>"I bark at that!"</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uxsatyrx.showPublicProfile?language=EN>xsatyrx</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 39<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(1/9/02 4:50:41 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1062.topic&index=12>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Guilds</span><hr size=1> I do understand that you may not have meant for me to take your post the way i did Dalninil, but observing how others may react, they may assume that it is Dhugal's JOB to correct a wrong that a member of his guild has commited. I wanted to assert that he have no responsibility to another's actions. Nor do i feel that any member of any guild does. One should be held accountable for One's own actions. <br><br>Now as stated well by good friend Valquiss and Ms. Silverbark, Guild Name is Valuable. Dhugal values his guild name only marginally less than his birthright. The player Behind Dhugal believes in guilds and supports the members in his to the extreme. I am this man.This is how i find enjoyment in the game, accomplishment is EVERYTHING.<br>Before i created Dhugal, i had a character by the name of Xelissen. Xelissen went out and did the Symbol of Tunare quest 3 times.(If you know this quest, then you might agree with me that this may be the most painful quest below the level of 30 in the whole game) He lost 7 levels while working on it with other members in his guild. U